---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import JsonLd from '~/components/common/JsonLd.astro';
import { SITE } from 'astrowind:config';

const metadata = {
  title: `UPF & UV Protection Technology — How It Works | ${SITE.name}`,
  description: `Deep dive into UPF/UV protection technology: how fiber-level UV stabilizers, dense weave constructions, and ceramic nanoparticles block 98%+ of UVA and UVB radiation. Testing methods, quality indicators, and applications.`,
  ignoreTitleTemplate: true,
};

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'UPF & UV Protection Technology',
  description: metadata.description,
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: SITE.name },
  datePublished: '2024-01-15',
  dateModified: '2025-06-01',
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <JsonLd data={jsonLd} />

  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
    <nav class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-8">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-sky-600">{SITE.name}</a>
      <span class="mx-2">/</span>
      <a href="/research" class="hover:text-sky-600">Research</a>
      <span class="mx-2">/</span>
      <span class="text-gray-900">UPF & UV Protection Technology</span>
    </nav>

    <div class="mb-4">
      <span class="inline-block text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-sky-600 bg-sky-50 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Sun Protection Technology</span>
      <span class="ml-3 text-sm text-gray-400">8 min read</span>
    </div>

    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">UPF & UV Protection Technology</h1>
    <p class="text-xl text-gray-500 mb-12 leading-relaxed">
      UPF/UV protection is the foundational technology that makes modern sun-protective clothing possible. It bridges the gap between everyday comfort and essential sun safety.
    </p>

    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none prose-headings:text-gray-900 prose-p:text-gray-600 prose-li:text-gray-600">
      <h2>What Is UPF?</h2>
      <p>
        UPF (Ultraviolet Protection Factor) measures how much UV radiation penetrates a fabric to reach the skin. A UPF 50 fabric allows 1/50th (2%) of UV radiation to pass through, blocking 98%. UPF 50+ blocks 98%+ and represents the maximum rating. Unlike SPF (which measures sunscreen protection), UPF measures physical fabric barrier protection that does not need reapplication.
      </p>
      <p>
        The result is a fabric that provides permanent sun protection that lasts the life of the garment — as long as the fabric structure remains intact.
      </p>

      <h2>How It Works: The Three Layers of Protection</h2>
      <p>
        Seekingtex UPF technology employs three complementary mechanisms for maximum UV blocking:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fiber-Level UV Stabilizers:</strong> Special chemical absorbers integrated into the polymer melt before fiber extrusion. These stabilizers absorb UV radiation and convert it to harmless heat energy. Because they are embedded in the fiber itself, not applied as a topical coating, they never wash off.</li>
        <li><strong>Dense Fabric Construction:</strong> Tightly woven or knitted structures minimize gaps between yarns where UV radiation can pass through. The tighter the construction, the higher the UPF rating.</li>
        <li><strong>Ceramic Nanoparticles:</strong> Advanced formulations include titanium dioxide (TiO2) and zinc oxide (ZnO) nanoparticles that scatter and reflect UV radiation, adding an additional layer of protection beyond absorption.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Testing & Certification</h2>
      <p>
        UPF rating is determined by standardized testing per AS/NZS 4399 or AATCC 183. A spectrophotometer measures UV transmission through the fabric at wavelengths from 290-400 nm. The result is expressed as a UPF rating. Seekingtex fabrics are lab-tested and certified to UPF 50+.
      </p>

      <h2>Key Quality Indicators</h2>
      <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-gray-100">
            <th class="p-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 border">Parameter</th>
            <th class="p-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 border">Standard</th>
            <th class="p-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 border">UPF 50+</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td class="p-3 border">UPF Rating</td><td class="p-3 border">15-24 (good)</td><td class="p-3 border">50+ (excellent)</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="p-3 border">UVA Transmission</td><td class="p-3 border">&lt;5%</td><td class="p-3 border">&lt;2%</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="p-3 border">UVB Transmission</td><td class="p-3 border">&lt;5%</td><td class="p-3 border">&lt;2%</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="p-3 border">Wash Durability</td><td class="p-3 border">20 washes (topical)</td><td class="p-3 border">50+ washes (fiber-level)</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="p-3 border">Fabric Weight</td><td class="p-3 border">120+ gsm required</td><td class="p-3 border">80+ gsm with technology</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Fibers Used</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Polyester:</strong> Naturally higher UPF than other fibers. Easily accepts UV stabilizers during extrusion (1-3% additive by weight).</li>
        <li><strong>Nylon:</strong> Lower inherent UV resistance but can achieve UPF 50+ with additive loadings of 2-5%.</li>
        <li><strong>Cotton:</strong> Low natural UPF (5-10). Requires heavy additive treatments. Not recommended for sun protection without special processing.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Fiber-Level vs. Topical UV Protection</h2>
      <p>
        Topical UV coatings are applied to finished fabric via padding or spraying. They provide UPF 15-30 initially but degrade rapidly with washing and wear. Fiber-level UV stabilizers are incorporated during fiber manufacturing, providing permanent protection that cannot wash off. Seekingtex exclusively uses fiber-level UV technology for all sun protection fabrics.
      </p>

      <h2>How Seekingtex Implements UPF Technology</h2>
      <p>
        Seekingtex uses fiber-level UV stabilizers across all UPF product lines. Our polyester and nylon yarns contain 2-3% UV absorbing additives by weight, integrated during the melt-spinning process. Combined with optimized knit and weave structures that minimize UV transmission gaps, our fabrics achieve certified UPF 50+ while maintaining soft hand and lightweight comfort.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200">
      <a href="/research" class="text-sky-600 hover:text-sky-700 font-medium">&larr; Back to Research</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
